In many traditions, naming has always been treated as powerful for exactly that reason:
	•	In the Genesis story, Adam names the animals — not to create them, but to recognize and distinguish them.
	•	In science, when a pattern gets a name — gravity, entropy, evolution — suddenly an entire field of knowledge becomes navigable.
	•	In computing, once a pattern is named — algorithm, object, network — engineers can reuse it and build on it.

The power isn’t mystical; it’s structural.
A name compresses complexity into a handle that minds can grab.

